      "content": "The nonviolent approach was absolutely the correct and most effective strategy because it successfully mobilized massive public support and forced the government to act without alienating the very people needed to pass the laws. While militant tactics like those of the Black Panthers or the Freedom Riders did highlight police brutality and demand immediate justice, they often failed to achieve the broad legislative victories that defined the movement's success. History shows that the disciplined, moral appeal of nonviolence convinced a reluctant nation to dismantle segregation, whereas violence often hardened opposition and stalled progress.",
